In [154]:
# Merge the forecast with the original data
df_forecast = forecast[['ds', 'yhat', 'yhat_lower', 'yhat_upper']]
df_combined = pd.merge(PM2_5[['ds', 'y']], df_forecast, on='ds', how='outer')

# Plot the historical data and forecasted data
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df_combined['ds'], df_combined['y'], label='Actual PM2.5', color='blue')
plt.plot(df_combined['ds'], df_combined['yhat'], label='Forecasted PM2.5', color='orange')
plt.fill_between(df_combined['ds'], df_combined['yhat_lower'], df_combined['yhat_upper'], color='orange', alpha=0.2)
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('PM2.5')
plt.title('Actual and Forecasted PM2.5 Levels')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

In [174]:
from sklearn.ensemble import AdaBoostRegressor, RandomForestRegressor, ExtraTreesRegressor
from sklearn.svm import SVR
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge, ElasticNet
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

# Define models
models = {
    'AdaBoost': AdaBoostRegressor(),
    'RandomForest': RandomForestRegressor(),
    'ExtraTrees': ExtraTreesRegressor(),
    'SVR': SVR(),
    'DecisionTree': DecisionTreeRegressor(),
    'Ridge': Ridge(),
    'ElasticNet': ElasticNet()  # Consider using ElasticNet for regression
}

# Compare models
results = {}
for name, model in models.items():
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
    results[name] = {'MSE': mse, 'R2': r2}
In [175]:
results_df = pd.DataFrame(results).T
results_df = results_df.sort_values(by='R2', ascending=False)  # Sort by R2 score

# Print the results
results_df

Model Performance Analysis¶

Metrics¶

  • Mean Squared Error (MSE): Measures the average squared difference between predicted and actual values. Lower values indicate better performance.
  • R-Squared (R2): Measures the proportion of variance in the target variable that is predictable from the features. Values closer to 1 indicate better model performance.

Model Results¶

  1. Ridge

    • MSE: 8.88 × 10^(-12) (very low)
    • R2: 1.000 (perfect fit)
    • Interpretation: The Ridge regression model performs exceptionally well with almost no error and a perfect R2 score, indicating it explains nearly all the variance in the target variable.

  2. ExtraTrees

    • MSE: 4.52 × 10^(-5) (very low)
    • R2: 1.000 (perfect fit)
    • Interpretation: The Extra Trees model also performs extremely well with very low MSE and a perfect R2 score, indicating it fits the data almost perfectly.

  3. RandomForest

    • MSE: 3.12 × 10^(-4) (low)
    • R2: 1.000 (perfect fit)
    • Interpretation: The RandomForest model has low MSE and a perfect R2 score, showing it explains most of the variance in the target variable with minimal error.

  4. ElasticNet

    • MSE: 5.66 × 10^(-4) (low)
    • R2: 1.000 (perfect fit)
    • Interpretation: The ElasticNet model also performs well with a very low MSE and perfect R2 score, indicating excellent performance.

  5. DecisionTree

    • MSE: 1.22 × 10^(-3) (low)
    • R2: 0.999999 (almost perfect fit)
    • Interpretation: The DecisionTree model shows very low MSE and nearly perfect R2 score, suggesting that it performs nearly as well as the previously mentioned models but with a slightly higher MSE.

  6. SVR

    • MSE: 7.61 (higher)
    • R2: 0.9957 (very high)
    • Interpretation: The SVR model has a significantly higher MSE compared to the other models but still explains a high proportion of the variance (very high R2). This indicates that while SVR has a higher prediction error, it still captures a significant amount of the data's variance.

  7. AdaBoost

    • MSE: 25.66 (highest)
    • R2: 0.9854 (high)
    • Interpretation: The AdaBoost model has the highest MSE and a lower R2 score compared to the others. This suggests it has a higher error in predictions compared to the other models but still explains a substantial portion of the variance in the target variable.

Summary¶

  • Best Performing Models: Ridge, ExtraTrees, and RandomForest show the best performance with very low MSE and perfect R2 scores.
  • Good Performance: ElasticNet and DecisionTree also perform very well with almost perfect R2 scores and low MSE.
  • Models with Higher Error: SVR and AdaBoost have higher MSE values, indicating higher prediction errors. Despite their high R2 scores, their performance is not as strong as the other models.

Overall, Ridge, ExtraTrees, and RandomForest are the top performers in your dataset, with nearly perfect predictions and explanations of variance.
